#1 Enter data

Killarney <- read.csv("~/BI612-homework/Killarney.csv")

#2 Create a boxplot of the species diversity by lake status. From the boxplot, does it look like there are any differences in plankton diversity among the lake types?

boxplot(Killarney$Diversity~Killarney$status,ylab = "Diversity",xlab = "Status")

From looking at the boxplot, it looks like there is a significant difference between the acidic lakes compared to the two other lake types.

#3 Run an ANOVA to test for differences in species diversity among the three lake types. Display the summary output.

my.fit=aov(Killarney$Diversity~Killarney$status)
summary(my.fit)
##                  Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
## Killarney$status  2  97.41   48.70   16.41 5.43e-06 ***
## Residuals        42 124.68    2.97                     
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

#4 What is the appropriate null hypethesis for the ANOVA?

The null hypethesis: there is a significant difference among lake types.

#5 What is the observed test statistic and p-value for the test?

observed test statistic: 16.41 p-value: 5.43e-06

#6 Did species diversity differ among these three lake types?

p<0.05, therefore there is a significant difference among lake types

#7 Run Tukey test and provide output

TukeyHSD(my.fit)

#8 Based on the follow-up test, which groups are significantly different from one another?

Based on the Tukey test, neutral and acidic, as well as recovered and acidic are significalty different from one another while recovered and neutral lakes are not.

#10a. Run a two-factor ANOVA to determine if the number of cancer cases depends on alcohol consumption, tobacco consumption, or their interaction

esoph <- read.csv("~/BI612-homework/esoph.csv")
my.fitt=aov(esoph$ncases~esoph$Alcohol*esoph$Tobacco)
summary(my.fitt)
##                             Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)
## esoph$Alcohol                3   46.9  15.624   2.085  0.110
## esoph$Tobacco                3   41.5  13.846   1.848  0.146
## esoph$Alcohol:esoph$Tobacco  9   31.5   3.501   0.467  0.892
## Residuals                   72  539.5   7.494

#10b.What is your conclusion about the effects of alcohol and tobacco based on this analysis? The ANOVA shows p-values>0.05, therefore we can infer that the number of cancer cases does not depend on alcohol consumtion, tobacco consumtion or their interaction.

#11c. What is your conclusion about the effects of ago and tobacco based on this analysis? Based on the ANOVA, we can conclude that there is a significance between the mean of the groups. When looking at the Tukey test we can conclude that the interactions between age: 45-54 & 25-34, 55-64 & 25-35, 65-74 & 25-34, 45-54 & 35-44, 55-64 & 35-44, 65-74 & 34-44, 75+ & 55-64, 75+ & 65-74 were all significant. And the interactions between tobacco: 20-29 & 0-9, 30+ & 0-9 were significant

#12a. Run a two-factor ANOVA to determine if the number of cases of esophageal cancer depends on age, alcohol consumption, or their interaction

my.fitt3=aov(esoph$ncases~esoph$Age*esoph$Alcohol)
summary(my.fitt3)

#13a.Make a scatterplot of weight (x-axis) versus fuel mileade (y-axis). Does fuel mileage seem to depend on weight?

plot(mtcars$wt~mtcars$mpg,xlab="Weight (1000 lbs)",ylab="Fuel Mileage (mpg)")

Fuel milaege does seem to depend on the weight of the car, a heavier car would result in less miles per gallon.

#13b. Perform a linear regression to determine if weight has an impact on fuel mileage

car1=glm(mtcars$mpg~mtcars$wt)
summary.lm(car1)

Equation: y=(-5.3445x)+37.2851

#13d. Is gas mileage significantly related to car weight? Provide p-value from regression results.

p-value= 1.294e-10, since p<0.05, gas mileage is significantly related to car weight.

The quarter mile time for a car with 300 horsepower would be 15.01 seconds.

#15a. Find two variables that you think might be correlated.

library(readr)
birthweight_reduced <- read.csv("~/BI612-homework/birthweight_reduced.csv")
birth=birthweight_reduced

#15b. Plot the relationship between the two variables using a scatterplot

plot(birth$Birthweight~birth$Gestation,ylab="Birthweight (lbs)",xlab="Gestation (weeks)")

#15c. Test for a correlation in R. What is the correlation coefficient?

cor.test(birth$Birthweight,birth$Gestation)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  birth$Birthweight and birth$Gestation
## t = 6.31, df = 40, p-value = 1.733e-07
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.5123421 0.8316893
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.7062919

The correlation coefficient is 0.7062919

#15d. Is the correlation significant? Provide the p-value from the test

p-value = 1.733e-07

p<0.05 therefore the correlation is significant.
